<font color="#FF0000">I DIDN'T SPIT ON ANYONE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 13:21:08 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Tim has read Authur's reply to Stephanie.<br><br>
He says he doesn't &quot;understand why the citizens of America would be so mean to returning Vietnam War Veterans.&quot;<br><br>
Well, the simple answer is -- they weren't.<br><br>
I was against the war from 1963, when I was 13.  I heard &amp; saw Buddhist monks -- not Communists -- setting themselves on fire to protest the oppression of the government WE supported.  I knew then we were on the wrong aside.  Against freedom of religion.  Against our own constitution.<br><br>
The only question was Why?  And what could I do about it?<br><br>
I never spit on anyone who went to Vietnam, I did everything I could to stop them from going in the first place.  To stop them from being killed, to stop them from killing, to stop them from fighting against everything our country is SUPPOSED to stand for. <br><br>
And when they came home.... Well, the Army was doing anything effective to deal with the trauma of the men returning.  Once again, it was the anti-war crowd that step into the breach.  <br><br>
The first rap-groups that allowed vets to get together and deal with their pain, the trauma of loss, their own feelings, and the difficulty -- often impossibility -- of communicatiing with others -- they were formed by anti-war psychologists and ordinary vets.  No Army brass, no officers, no help from Unlce Same at all.<br><br>
And me, personally?  I hitchhiked around alot in the late 60s &amp; 70s.  Went across country quite a few times.  By far the biggest chunk of people who picked me up we Vietnam vets.  The story was always the same -- no one at home wanted to hear what they had to say.  <br><br>
More often than not it weas precisely because what they had to say was how horrible and senseless the war was.  The people at home KNEW that, of course, but they didn't want to have to confront it -- for then they would have to confront that THEIR government was responsible, and since this is SUPPOSED to be a democracy, that would mean THEY were responsible.<br><br>
So this is how those talks would generally go.  First, they'd tell me how no one would listen to them.  Then they'd tell me their horror stories.  Mostly, I'd just listen, draw them out when they seemed to be struggling whether to say something or not, but mostly, I'd just listen.<br><br>
Then, just before they'd let me off, I'd tell them something like this: 'You know, the reason folks don't want to listen to you isn't because of you.  It's because of them.  Because they don't want to face up to what it means, that the government lied to them, and this is a democracy, and it's on them to do something.  It's really screwed up, but YOU'RE not the one who's screwed up.  Keep looking for ways to tell the truth.  That's REAL patriotism.'<br><br>
EVERY one of them thanked me sincerely when I got out.<br><br>
Of all the men I met, exactly ONE thought that we were right to be fighting in Vietnam.  But even he had his horror stories that no one in town wanted to hear.  Even he thanked me for listening, for seeing &amp; hearing him, no matter what he had to say.<br><br>
Finally, the really big picture -- the reason that the War finally ended:  The Army &amp; Marines -- and even, finally, the Air Force joined the anti-War movement.  There's an out-of-print book, _Soldiers In Revolt_ that tells the story, you can find it in a good college library.  It's the biggest open secret left from the War.  The enlisted men went AWOL, deserted, refused to go into combat, wore peace signs, black armbands on Moratorium day -- and even fragged their officers on occasion.  THEY were the reason the War finally ended.<br><br>
Tim says &quot;The Vietnam War Veterans were simply patriots and good Americans that went to war for their Country.&quot;<br><br>
Of course, that was what they beleived when they went.  They didn;t know any better.  But they learned otherwise rather quickly.  The men who sent them their knew better all along.<br><br>
Tim goes on, &quot;I guess I don't understand the mindset that was going on at the time?&quot;<br><br>
No, you don't.  And there's a solution to that: READ.  What makes a democracy work is that people are RESPONSIBLE for what their government does.  They can't be responsible if they don't know what's going on.  And you can't understand the present if you don't understand the past.<br><br>
Tim asks, &quot;Did the war protesters blame the soldier for the USA's involvement?&quot;<br><br>
No.  We set up all kinds of support systems to help (1) people avoid becoming soldiers in the first place (2) soldiers who'd finished basic training get out of going to Vietnam (3) soldiers who'd served come to terms with what they'd seen and done.<br><br>
Of course, the Anti-War Movement got so big, and so diverse there were bound to be some who were out of control, along with the government agents who intentionally did things to make us look bad, and to get us fighting amongst ourselves.  So, yes, there were some INDIVIDUALS who blamed the soldiers.  But the Anti-War organizations were all quite clear that the soldiers were not the enemy, but front-line victims of betrayal.  If we had not had that attitude, we would have never won over so many soldiers that the War was finally ended.<br><br>
Tim concludes, <br><br>
&quot;I am only 32 years old. I think I remember the war on the news when my parents watched the news at night. People my age really do not know very much about war. I know I don't.&quot;<br><br>
This is very good.  You don't know much, but you KNOW that you don't know much.  Everyone who lived through that time will have their own story to tell, their own perspective, and all are valuable.  But you must also have an historical understanding to place indivudual experience in context.<br><br>
Some useful books to do that: <br><br>
&quot;The Vietnam Wars&quot; by Marilyn Young.  This begins with the French.  It's a relatively short book that covers a broad period of time.  Recommended as the first history book you should read.<br><br>
&quot;A Bright Shining Lie&quot; by Neil Sheehan.  A view from inside the War.  Shoots down many of the myths that you will hear repeated over and over again.<br><br>
&quot;The Perfect War&quot; by James William Gibson.  Analyzes the military approach to Vietnam.  A unique perspective on the military assumptions and practices that blinded the military machine to the obvious.<br><br>
&quot;Who Spoke Up? American Protest Against the War in Vietnam 1963-1975&quot; by Nancy Zaroulis and Gerald Sullivan.  The title  says it all.<br><br>
&quot;Home From the War: Learning from Vietnam Veterans&quot; Robert Jaty Lifton. Lifton helped start the first rap group.  He helped Vets to begin the process of healing themselves.<br><br>
And, finally 3 books about Vietnam's effect on our culture, how we've tried to come to terms with it.<br><br>
&quot;The Legacy: The Vietnam War in the American Imaginiation&quot; Edited by D. Michael Shafer.<br><br>
&quot;Warrior Dreams: Paramilitary Culture in Post-Veitnam America&quot; by James William Gibson.<br><br>
&quot;Echoes of Combat: The Vietnam War in American Memory&quot; by Fred Turner (just published).<br><br>
And, finally, a reminder from a song by Love, one of the cutting edge bands of the time:<br><br>
&quot;Write the rules <br>
In the sky<br>
But ask your leaders,<br>
'Why?'&quot;<br><br>
Paul Rosenberg<br>
